linux boot information
-----------------------
1. generated by the kernel (via printk)
2. generated by userspace (usually init and systemd)


log
---
$ sudo cat /var/log/kern.log
$ sudo cat /var/log/kern.log.1

$ sudo cat /var/log/boot.log
$ sudo cat /var/log/boot.log.1


$ sudo cat /var/log/dmesg
$ sudo cat /var/log/dmesg.0


journalctl vs /var/log/journal
-------------------------------
diminish the size of the journal
$ sudo journalctl --vacuum-size=100M
$ sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=1s
$ sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=2d

/etc/systemd/journald.conf
SystemMaxUse=100M

$ journalctl --list-boots

# last boot
$ journalctl -b

# last boot -1
$ journalctl -b -1

# usig _BOOT_ID
$ journalctl _BOOT_ID=156019a44a774a0bb0148a92df4af81b

# using _PID, _UID

# using _TRANSPORT=kernel, stdout, ...
$ journalctl -b _TRANSPORT=kernel
$ journalctl -b _TRANSPORT=stdout

# service unit _SYSTEMD_UNIT=   or -u

$ journalctl /usr/lib/systemd/systemd -b 

systemd-analyze plot > ss.svg



Enter GRUB menu
----------------
$ sudo vi /etc/default/grub
# GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=hidden
# GRUB_HIDDEN_TIMEOUT=
# GRUB_TIMEOUT=0
GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=menu

$ sudo update-grub

$ sudo reboot

Press [Shift] key to enter GRUB menu

with BIOS [Shift] key     -> GNU GRUB menu
with UEFI [Esc] key       -> GNU GRUB menu


Select default linux-image
--------------------------
$ sudo vi /etc/default/grub
GRUB_DEFAULT=saved
GRUB_SAVEDEFAULT=true

$ sudo update-grub


